info.title: FastAPI
info.description:
- Browser
    - CDP: [/cdp/json/version](/cdp/json/version)
- Jupyter
    - Notebook: [/jupyter](/jupyter)
- MCP
    - Streamable HTTP: [/mcp](/mcp) or [/v1/mcp](/v1/mcp)

post.description:
Execute command in the specified shell session
Supports SSE streaming if Accept header contains 'text/event-stream'

View output of the specified shell session
Supports SSE streaming if Accept header contains 'text/event-stream'
Wait for the process in the specified shell session to return
Write input to the process in the specified shell session
Terminate the process in the specified shell session

Create a new shell session and return its ID
If id already exists, return the existing session

get.description: Create a new shell session and return the terminal URL

delete.description: Manually cleanup a specific shell session

post.description: Read file content

Write file content (supports both text and binary files)

For binary files, set encoding to 'base64' and provide base64-encoded content.
For text files, use default 'utf-8' encoding.
Replace string in file
Search in file content
Find files by name pattern
Upload file using streaming
List path contents with flexible options

An filesystem editor tool that allows the agent to
- view
- create
- navigate
- edit files
The tool parameters are defined by Anthropic and are not editable.

Execute Python code using Jupyter kernel with session persistence

This endpoint allows you to execute Python code and get results back.
You can optionally specify a kernel_name (defaults to 'python3').
Use session_id to maintain variable state across multiple requests.
Sessions automatically expire after 30 minutes of inactivity.

get.description: Get information about available Jupyter kernels

post.description: Create a new Jupyter session

Execute JavaScript code using Node.js

This endpoint allows you to execute JavaScript code and get results back.
Each request creates a fresh execution environment that's cleaned up automatically.

get.description: Get information about Node.js runtime and available languages

List all available tools from the specified MCP server

Args:
    server_name: The name of the MCP server as defined in mcp-servers.json

Returns:
    Response containing the list of available tools with their descriptions and parameters

post.description:
Execute a specific tool on the specified MCP server

Args:
    server_name: The name of the MCP server as defined in mcp-servers.json
    tool_name: The name of the tool to execute
    arguments: Tool arguments dictionary

Returns:
    Response containing the tool execution results

command.title: Command
command.description: The commands to run. Allowed options are: `view`, `create`, `str_replace`, `insert`, `undo_edit`.

path.title: Path
path.description: Absolute path to file or directory, e.g. `/workspace/file.py` or `/workspace`.

file_text.title: File Text
file_text.description: Required parameter of `create` command, with the content of the file to be created.

old_str.title: Old Str
old_str.description: Required parameter of `str_replace` command containing the string in `path` to replace.

new_str.title: New Str
new_str.description: Optional parameter of `str_replace` command containing the new string (if not given, no string will be added). Required parameter of `insert` command containing the string to insert.

insert_line.title: Insert Line
insert_line.description: Required parameter of `insert` command. The `new_str` will be inserted AFTER the line `insert_line` of `path`.

view_range.title: View Range
view_range.description: Optional parameter of `view` command when `path` points to a file. If none is given, the full file is shown. If provided, the file will be shown in the indicated line number range, e.g. [11, 12] will show lines 11 and 12. Indexing at 1 to start. Setting `[start_line, -1]` shows all lines from `start_line` to the end of the file.

ToolAnnotations.title: ToolAnnotations
ToolAnnotations.description:
Additional properties describing a Tool to clients.

NOTE: all properties in ToolAnnotations are **hints**.
They are not guaranteed to provide a faithful description of
tool behavior (including descriptive properties like `title`).

Clients should never make tool use decisions based on ToolAnnotations
received from untrusted servers.
